    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1qIR1NBUiJ1R",
        "colab_type": "text"
      },
      "source": [
        "It does not converge, the generator does not learn to produce 0's and loss does not decrease. Even if we manage to find a way to train so that it converges, ideally we would want something that would be able to converge in this situation as well.  \n",
        "\n",
        "This issue was described in [famous Wasserstein GAN paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1701.07875). In this paper authors proposed to change binary clasification to something that measures distance between generated outputs and real examples. \n",
        "\n",
        "Let's try it out with our simplified example. "
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DjQmDezd8Zys",
        "colab_type": "text"
      },
      "source": [
        "## WGAN"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "q5i18Me3jsz6",
        "colab_type": "text"
      },
      "source": [
        "A very naive approach would be to measure Euclidean distance between real  and generated distributions. Lets see if that helps."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "nckTzSv3Rbe0",
        "colab_type": "code",
        "outputId": "79f8b56a-6843-4513-e241-35bd8aea5aee",
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 449
        }
      },
      "source": [
        "def euclidean_distance(x):\n",
        "  return tf.reduce_mean(tf.norm(x, 'euclidean'))\n",
        "\n",
        "train_generator(euclidean_distance)"
      ],
