      "source": [
        "Code above actually is in line with WGAN except as I mentioned before we are mising a method to enforce Lipschitz constraint. Three main changes are:\n",
        " - we removed sigmoid from last layer of discriminator\n",
        " - we change loss of discriminator to be the distance between real and generated outputs of discriminator\n",
        " - we change generator loss to be just opposite to discriminator loss for generated input. \n",
        "\n",
        "We can see that this algorithm converges and generated distribution approaches 0. This is all nice and good, however, as you can see, discriminator loss is actually a negative number, hence practitioners more often uses some sort of not saturating loss. For example, hinge loss which is defined as follows:"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jpIbi73Z9aGi",
        "colab_type": "code",
        "colab": {}
      },
      "source": [
        "def d_loss_hinge(d_score_z, d_score_r):\n",
        "    d_loss_real = tf.nn.relu(1.0 - d_score_r) # Note: this changed\n",
        "    d_loss_fake = tf.nn.relu(1.0 + d_score_z) # Note: this changed\n",
        "    return tf.reduce_mean(d_loss_real) + tf.reduce_mean(d_loss_fake) "
      ],
      "execution_count": 0,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
